Let me compare the gun_point computation between D1 and D2 OCaml, and between D2 OCaml and C.

**C code (D2 ai.cpp lines 934-946):**
```cpp
if ((previous_visibility || !(obj_ref & 3)) && ready_to_fire(robptr, ailp) && (dist_to_player < F1_0 * 200) && (robptr->n_guns) && !(robptr->attack_type)) {
    if (ailp->next_fire <= 0)
        calc_gun_point(&gun_point, obj, aip->CURRENT_GUN);
    else
        calc_gun_point(&gun_point, obj, 0);
    vis_vec_pos = gun_point;
} else {
    vis_vec_pos = obj->pos;
}
```

**D1 OCaml (line 884):**
```ocaml
if !next_fire <= 0 && !dist_to_player < f1_0 * 200 && n_guns > 0 && attack_type = 0
```

The D1 condition is missing the `previous_visibility` and `ready_to_fire` checks that appear in the C D2 version. The C code also branches on whether `next_fire <= 0` to decide which gun to use, whereas D1 seems to have a simpler structure.

Looking at the D2 OCaml code around line 1790, it receives a pre-computed gun_point from C through the bridge, so it doesn't need to calculate it itself. But the D1 OCaml code at line 884 appears to handle gun point calculation differently. Let me trace through how the visibility vector position gets set in each version to understand the actual differences.

